7. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFCE6FBE0FB3A1803" authority="Hepper" authorityName="Hepper" box="[872,1162,1099,1121]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
Solanum linnaeanum 
<bibCitation id="5E032534FFC6FFDCFBCEFBE0FC7D181F" author="Hepper &amp; P.-M. L. Jaeger" journal="Kew Bull." page="435" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" score="22.239024375395413" volume="41" year="1986">Hepper &amp; P.-M.L.Jaeger, Kew Bull. 41: 435. 1986</bibCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3337ED3FFC6FFDCFCEEFB32FB3C1961" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B962D58FFC6FFDCFCEEFB32FB3C1961" blockId="8.[840,1479,1177,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Distribution. Probably native to South Africa and naturalised around the Mediterranean in disturbed, often coastal, habitats worldwide; sand dunes, grass, forest margins, river banks, and roadsides at 
<quantity id="4CD180BDFFC6FFDCFC4DFB46FB961961" box="[963,1062,1261,1283]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="m" value="600.0" valueMax="1200.0" valueMin="0.0">0–1200 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3337ED3FFC6FFDCFCEEFAA1FC271BC6" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B962D58FFC6FFDCFCEEFAA1FC271BC6" blockId="8.[840,1479,1177,1956]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFCEEFAA1FBA71942" box="[864,1047,1290,1312]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFCEEFAA1FBA71942" box="[864,1047,1290,1312]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has long been referred to has 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFAF1FAA1FC79195E" authority="L." authorityName="L." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sodomaeum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFAF1FAA1FC15195E" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum sodomaeum</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFC72FA8DFB42195E" authority="Dunal" authorityName="Dunal" box="[1020,1266,1318,1340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hermannii">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFC72FA8DFB13195E" box="[1020,1187,1318,1340]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum hermannii</emphasis>
Dunal
</taxonomicName>
, the latter name is illegitimate and the former has been rejected according to the rules of botanical nomenclature and can therefore not be used [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFA0EFAF5FA2E1916" author="Hepper FN &amp; Jaeger P-ML" box="[1408,1438,1374,1396]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="433 - 435" part="41" refId="ref11690" refString="50. Hepper FN, Jaeger P-ML (1986) Name changes for two Old World Solanum species. Kew Bull 41: 433 - 435." title="Name changes for two Old World Solanum species" type="journal article" year="1986">50</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFA2CFAF5FA0D1916" author="McNeill J &amp; Barrie FR &amp; Buck WR &amp; Demoulin V &amp; Greuter W" box="[1442,1469,1374,1396]" journalOrPublisher="Regnum Vegetabile" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" part="154" refId="ref11717" refString="51. McNeill J, Barrie FR, Buck WR, Demoulin V, Greuter W, et al. (2012) International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. Konigstein: Koelz Scientific Books." title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011" type="journal article" year="2012">51</bibRefCitation>
]. This species is probably native to South Africa and has been introduced into the Mediterranean region where it is now common. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFC24FA19FBE719A5" box="[938,1111,1458,1479]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFC24FA19FBE719A5" box="[938,1111,1458,1479]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically quite distinct from the rest of the eggplant wild relatives with its deeply incised, almost glabrous leaves (
<figureCitation id="131231DDFFC6FFDCFC62FA41FB831A62" box="[1004,1075,1514,1536]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
). In Spain, fruits of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFA8DFA41FACC199D" box="[1283,1404,1514,1535]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFA8DFA41FACC199D" box="[1283,1404,1514,1535]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not appear to be eaten by any animals, it is common to find fruits from several years still on the plant. The relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFABBF989FA1C1A55" box="[1333,1452,1570,1591]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFABBF989FA1C1A55" box="[1333,1452,1570,1591]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the eggplant wild relatives was first clearly shown by Weese and Bohs [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFC04F9F1FC171A12" author="Weese TL &amp; Bohs L" box="[906,935,1626,1648]" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="49 - 56" part="59" refId="ref10863" refString="27. Weese TL, Bohs L (2010) Eggplant origins: out of Africa, into the Orient. Taxon 59: 49 - 56." title="Eggplant origins: out of Africa, into the Orient" type="journal article" year="2010">27</bibRefCitation>
]. It was previously used as the female parent in the creation of the first linkage map for eggplants [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFA8DF9DDFAAF1AEE" author="Doglanar S &amp; Frary A &amp; Daunay M-C &amp; Lester RN &amp; Tanksley SD" box="[1283,1311,1654,1676]" journalOrPublisher="Genetics" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1697 - 1711" part="161" refId="ref11780" refString="52. Doglanar S, Frary A, Daunay M-C, Lester RN, Tanksley SD (2002) A comparative genetic linkage map of eggplant (Solanum melongena L.) and its implications for genome evolution in the Solanaceae. Genetics 161: 1697 - 1711." title="A comparative genetic linkage map of eggplant (Solanum melongena L.) and its implications for genome evolution in the Solanaceae" type="journal article" year="2002">52</bibRefCitation>
] despite the cross only proving possible through embryo rescue (M.-C. Daunay, pers. comm.). The accession used by Weese and Bohs [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFAF9F905FA231AA6" author="Weese TL &amp; Bohs L" box="[1399,1427,1710,1732]" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="49 - 56" part="59" refId="ref10863" refString="27. Weese TL, Bohs L (2010) Eggplant origins: out of Africa, into the Orient. Taxon 59: 49 - 56." title="Eggplant origins: out of Africa, into the Orient" type="journal article" year="2010">27</bibRefCitation>
] was Mediterranean in origin, so the relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFA95F961FA241ABD" box="[1307,1428,1738,1759]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFA95F961FA241ABD" box="[1307,1428,1738,1759]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the other South African species 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFB1AF94DFAA41A99" box="[1172,1300,1766,1787]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFB1AF94DFAA41A99" box="[1172,1300,1766,1787]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is intriguing and perhaps indicative that it is introduced in the Mediterranean. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFCC6F8B5FC4C1B51" box="[840,1020,1822,1843]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFCC6F8B5FC4C1B51" box="[840,1020,1822,1843]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been used in analyses of resistance to important diseases such as bacterial wilt [
<bibRefCitation id="EFB850A9FFC6FFDCFB6CF891FB4D1B32" author="Lebeau A &amp; Daunay M-C &amp; Frary A &amp; Palloix A &amp; Wang J-F" box="[1250,1277,1850,1872]" journalOrPublisher="Phytopathology" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="154 - 165" part="101" refId="ref11829" refString="53. Lebeau A, Daunay M-C, Frary A, Palloix A, Wang J-F, et al. (2011) Bacterial wilt resistance in tomato, pepper and eggplant: genetic resources respond to diverse strains in the Ralstonia solanacearum complex. Phytopathology 101: 154 - 165." title="Bacterial wilt resistance in tomato, pepper and eggplant: genetic resources respond to diverse strains in the Ralstonia solanacearum complex" type="journal article" year="2011">53</bibRefCitation>
] and, similarly to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2956DBFFC6FFDCFA3BF891FC3D1B09" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis id="B95DF14AFFC6FFDCFA3BF891FC3D1B09" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a candidate for the creation of ILs that would be valuable resources for eggplant breeding (M.-C. Daunay, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
